ee lieutenants from salt-blood tears without unbinding their debts\", \"Seal the Night Market culvert wheel map behind a new oath accessible only by public need\"],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Knife-Whisper Pell\", \"lines\": \"You come with the river’s shadow on your shoulders and your reflection lagging a heartbeat behind you, and I know a broker when the city tries to pretend it still believes in saints. My ledger is full of names that learned to keep quiet because speaking turned teeth into coin for other mouths, and those mouths are still hungry. The curse you smell on my people is salt turned inward, a punishment meant to teach silence by drowning the tongue, and it has done nothing but teach grief how to keep time. Free them from the river’s bad memory, and I will barter with better ones; I will leash my knives to rules sharp enough to cut me if I pull, so long as those rules do not starve us while the Wardens fatten their toll plates. Say it clean, Lio Fenwater: write me into this city like a clause that binds the knifework to a cause, or write me out like a heresy and trust that your mercy will not split like glass.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lio Fenwater\", \"lines\": \"I came to cut breath-holes, not throats, and to teach chains the trick of loosening without turning into new gallows. The Soft-Cut will not unmake your debts or your choices; it will peel the curse away from the ledger like lifting a wet label from a bottle, slow and careful, using salt where salt once burned to cleanse instead of to accuse. End your masking games at the Loom of Tides and stand witness where witnesses count—in the Scriptorium of Oaths and beneath this arch that holds the city’s spine—and I will set a chair for you with language that sits crooked on purpose. You will feel every splinter of public duty, and when you try to lean away, the words will bite until you remember why you asked for breath. I don’t promise comfort, Pell, but I promise you won’t be