s, and I will pack them away if your chair lets me breathe without having to steal air from someone else’s lungs. Exile is a word I can swallow for a season if it keeps my people from coughing salt in their sleep, and oversight is a word I can learn to love if it does not turn into a gag when the Wardens feel nervous. But hear me: if you dress a knife in scripture and call it a seat, I will feel it, and I will not be the only one to bleed. Cut clean, Lio, and I will open my ledger on the brass benches and let the city read me for once without having to guess which parts I set in shadow.\"}\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Exile the Knife\", \"text\": \"Demand that Pell take exile for a season and a day beyond Miravale’s bridges, surrendering operational sway while a deputy submits to witness and audit, in exchange for the Soft-Cut performed tonight. Speak the terms beneath the Starspan so the basalt remembers, invoking the Order to bell the boundary and the Archivists to plate it in brass so the city can point to it when tempers flare. Promise safe-conduct out and back, so the exile is not an execution in prettier clothes, and swear that the deputy’s ledger will be examined on festival days when the Loom’s song is clearest. Declare that masking at the Loom ends now and forever under pain of banishment becoming banishment made permanent, and that the Night Market’s peace will be kept by the same rules that keep river locks from eating their own gears. Promise also that you will seal the culvert wheel behind a public-need key, so no single creed—smuggler, Warden, or saint—can open it without the city’s hunger testifying to need.\", \"outcome\": \"Pell’s face tightens like a knot pulled true, then loosens as if a splinter works its way free, and they accept exile with a wry bow that looks like a blade turned flat. The Soft-Cut rides your chime-plate’s trembling note and the salt-bowl’s sting, and three lieutenants cough brine that 